# .cursorrules — University Consultation Booking App

## Project Context

This is a web application for scheduling university consultations between students and professors. Three roles: student, professor, admin.
The app is currently developed and run locally. AWS deployment comes later — everything built now must be designed to move to AWS with minimal rework.
The chatbot logic is currently rule-based (keyword matching, fuzzy matching) and runs without an LLM. In the future, all chatbot logic will be replaced by an AWS AI service — code must be written so that replacement is a minimal intervention.

---

## 1. ARCHITECTURAL RULES — never break these

### Separation of concerns

- All business logic lives exclusively in `backend/services/` — never directly in routers
- Routers are thin: validate input (Pydantic), call service, return response — nothing more
- The frontend must never compute anything that depends on business rules (e.g. whether exam period is active, which consultation types are available) — that always comes from the backend
- Every page reads data only through `api/client.js` — never a raw fetch inside a component

### Chatbot isolation (critical for future AWS migration)

- All chatbot logic must live in `backend/services/chat_service.py` — not a single line of parsing, intent detection, or response generation logic belongs in `backend/routers/chat.py`
- The `chat.py` router may only do this:
  ```python
  @router.post("/chat")
  async def chat(msg: ChatMessage, user=Depends(get_current_user), db=Depends(get_db)):
      response = await chat_service.process(msg.text, user.id, db)
      return response
  ```
- `chat_service.py` must expose a clearly defined interface:
  ```python
  async def process(text: str, student_id: int, db) -> ChatResponse
  ```
  When AWS AI arrives, only `chat_service.py` changes — the router, frontend, and DB remain untouched.
- Conversation context (`ParsedContext`) is stored exclusively in the `conversations.state` JSONB column — never in server memory, never in the frontend

### EmailProvider abstraction

- Never call SendGrid directly from application code — always go through `services/email_service.py`
- Interface:
  ```python
  class EmailProvider:
      async def send(self, to: str, subject: str, body: str) -> None: ...
  ```
- `EMAIL_PROVIDER=console|sendgrid` in `.env` determines which implementation is used
- When AWS SES arrives, add `SESEmailProvider` — nothing else changes

### Configuration

- No business value may be hardcoded in application code:
  - ❌ `if votes >= 5:`
  - ✅ `threshold = await get_config("auto_schedule_vote_threshold", db)`
- All values live in the `system_config` table (key/value)
- Default values are set only in `seed.py`, never in application code

### Database

- Always use async SQLAlchemy sessions — never sync
- Never write raw SQL strings — use SQLAlchemy ORM or the `select()` builder
- Every mutation (INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE) must be accompanied by a write to `audit_log` — `audit_middleware.py` does this automatically; do not write it manually in services unless it is a special case
- Migrations exclusively through Alembic — never `CREATE TABLE` or `ALTER TABLE` directly

### Authentication and authorization

- Every endpoint must have `Depends(get_current_user)` and a role check
- Role checks must be applied via a decorator in `auth_middleware.py`, not inline in each endpoint:
  ```python
  @require_role("student")
  @router.get("/bookings/mine")
  ```
- Thesis consultation slots additionally verify `ThesisApplication.status == ACTIVE` on the backend — hiding in the UI is not sufficient

